    "plan_content": "## Plan Summary\n\nHere's the complete plan to add `Bun.INI` following the exact same pattern as `Bun.TOML`, `Bun.JSONC`, `Bun.JSON5`, and `Bun.YAML`:\n\n### Files to touch (6 total)\n\n| Action | File |\n|--------|------|\n| **Create** | `src/bun.js/api/INIObject.zig` |\n| Edit | `src/bun.js/api.zig` |\n| Edit | `src/bun.js/api/BunObject.zig` (4 places) |\n| Edit | `src/bun.js/bindings/BunObject+exports.h` |\n| Edit | `src/bun.js/bindings/BunObject.cpp` |\n| Edit | `packages/bun-types/bun.d.ts` |\n\n### Key decisions\n\n1. **Self-contained INI parser** — The internal `src/ini.zig` requires a `DotEnv.Loader` (it's built for npm config), so `INIObject.zig` implements its own simple line-by-line parser. No `bun.ini` import.\n\n2. **`parse`** — Walks lines, skips `;`/`#` comments and blank lines, handles `[section]` headers (creating nested JS objects, including dotted section names like `[a.b.c]`), and splits `key = value` pairs. Throws a `SyntaxError` for malformed lines.\n\n3. **`stringify`** — Uses `wtf.StringBuilder` (same as JSON5Object.zig). First emits top-level flat `key = value` pairs, then emits `[section]` blocks for nested object-valued properties.\n\n4. **Wiring pattern** — Identical to TOML/JSON5/YAML: `BunObject.zig` exposes a lazy property callback + getter function; the C++ header macro adds `macro(INI)` alphabetically between `Glob` and `JSON5`; the `.cpp` hash table gets one new `PropertyCallback` entry.\n\n5. **TypeScript** — `namespace INI` with `parse(input: string): Record<string, any>` and `stringify(input: Record<string, any>): string`, inserted between the `TOML` and `JSONC` namespaces (~line 794 in `bun.d.ts`).",
